  	  {
  	    "@context": "http://schema.org",
  	    "@type": "NewsArticle",
  	    "headline": "How to Protect Your New Bike from Thieves",
  	    "alternativeHeadline": "",
  	    "url": "http://gq.com/story/how-to-protect-your-bike-from-thieves",
  	    "image": ["http://media.gq.com/photos/55b94487b6a585c04cb5aee9/master/pass/bike-gif5.gif"],
  	    "thumbnailUrl": "http://media.gq.com/photos/55b94487b6a585c04cb5aee9/master/pass/bike-gif5.gif",
  	    "datePublished": "2015-07-29T21:08:01.070Z",
  	    "dateModified": "2015-07-30T13:47:14.946Z",
  	    "articleSection": "News &amp; Culture",
  	    "description": "",
  	    "articleBody": "FacebookPinterest\u000A\u000ASo you\u0027ve decided to join the all-powerful bike lobby? Congratulations! Here, have a complimentary pennyfarthing for contributing to America\u0027s 60% surge in ridership over the past decade. Now for the bad news: The spike in ridership has come alongside a dramatic spike in bike theft, too. \u000A\u000ASure, some scale of theft is inevitable. But there are still some simple steps you can take to defend yourself from would-be thieves. \u000A\u000ASTEP 1: PREVENTIONOne of the best ways to safeguard your bike is also one of the most commonly overlooked: knowing its serial number. \u000A\u000A\u0022It\u0027s the single most important thing you can have if the bike goes missing,\u0022 says Bryan Hance of Bike Index, a digital bike registry. Photos and unique characteristics — a sticker here, a funky component there — are helpful for post-theft identification, but the serial number \u0022is the only thing that\u0027s going to prove that particular bike being sold on craigslist is yours.\u0022\u000A\u000AYou don\u0027t need to be a bike wizard to find that number either. It\u0027s typically engraved beneath the bottom bracket or on one of a few other easy-to-spot places.\u000A\u000ARegistering that information with the police can aid in recovery on a local scale. But these municipal databases suffer from a critical flaw: Bikes are highly mobile, and pro thieves often ship their hauls far away to reduce the risk of being caught. \u0022Bike theft isn\u0027t a local problem,\u0022 says Officer Matt Friedman, who heads San Francisco\u0027s anti-bike-theft unit. \u0022It\u0027s a universal problem.\u0022\u000A\u000AEnter the Internet. Several services—including the aforementioned Bike Index—allow cyclists to register their serial numbers for free. The result: Universal, searchable repositories for police and private citizens to track stolen bikes anywhere. That way, a bike stolen in Boston and confiscated in Oakland can still find its way back home.\u000A\u000A\u0022Instead of these little balkanized databases we have this one crazy big one,\u0022 Hance says.\u000A\u000A\u0022Your bike doesn\u0027t have to be impossible to steal. It just has to be harder to steal than the bikes around it.\u0022Twitter\u000A\u000ASTEP 2: PROTECTIONYou\u0027re almost ready to ride. First, though, you\u0027ll need a good lock.\u000A\u000A\u0022But my bike is garbage!\u0022 you might say. \u0022No one would want that rusted heap plastered with Lisa Frank stickers.\u0022 Then a thief hauls your rusted heap plastered and its Lisa Frank stickers off to a chop shop.\u000A\u000AThe truth is most thieves don\u0027t care about a bike\u0027s condition or branding. \u0022I talk to a lot of people that say things like ‘I\u0027m glad that it looks kind of crappy because thieves won\u0027t want it,\u0027\u0022 says Emily Thibodeau, owner of Hub Bicycle in Cambridge, Mass.  \u0022And that is completely untrue.\u0022\u000A\u000A\u0022They are looking for the easiest bike to steal,\u0022 she says. \u0022That\u0027s pretty much it.\u0022\u000A\u000AYou don\u0027t need to go full Pee Wee Herman when you lock up — not that it helped him, anyway — but if you\u0027re riding in an urban environment, you\u0027ll want something beefier than the cheapo coil from your childhood Huffy.  \u000A\u000A\u0022Cable locks are terrible,\u0022 Hance says. \u0022You can go to Home Depot and get a tool for $40 to cut right through them.\u0022\u000A\u000AFacebookPinterest\u000A\u000AIf you don\u0027t mind lugging the extra weight, bulky chain locks offer the best protection since they are the most difficult to cut. For most riders though, U-locks are adequate. (At least now that they can\u0027t be hacked with basic Bic pens.) Among U-locks, smaller is better because it leaves less room for a thief to get good leverage. Just make sure you secure the frame of the bike, or you may return to a single forlorn wheel, lock fully intact. Good luck riding that home! \u000A\u000AIt should go without saying, but ensure you lock your rig to an immovable object, too. Though rare, thieves have been known to deploy dummy poles or saw through trees to pilfer bikes. And if you have easily detachable components—wheels with quick release skewers, lights, panniers—either lock them up or take them with you. If you don\u0027t take them, a thief gladly will. (Quick release skewers can also be replaced with more secure locking mechanisms.)\u000A\u000AAs for locking technique, one of the most secure—albeit counterintuitive—methods involves placing a u-lock around only the rear rim and inside the rear triangle. Popularized by bike guru Sheldon Brown, the eponymous locking method makes it impossible to remove the rear rim from the rest of the bike, thus anchoring everything without actually placing the lock around the frame. \u000A\u000AOther effective methods involve using multiple locks, or using multiple types of locks. Both strategies force crooks to up their games, with the latter also requiring them to have several tools on hand.\u000A\u000A\u0022Bike theft is about time,\u0022 Friedman says. \u0022No lock is 100 percent theft-proof. But if you can slow down a thief, then you\u0027re doing your job.\u0022\u000A\u000AIn other words, securing a bike is like that old joke about outrunning a bear: Your bike doesn\u0027t have to be impossible to steal. It just has to be harder to steal than the bikes around it.\u000A\u000ASTEP 3: RECOVERYNationwide, an estimated $350 million worth of bikes go missing every year. And the success rate on returning those bikes is depressingly low: One study concluded only 2.4% of stolen bikes make it back home. Still, that doesn\u0027t mean you should sigh and give up if your bike goes missing. \u000A\u000AFirst, file a police report. It sounds like a no-brainer, but most bike thefts are never reported.\u000A\u000A\u0022People feel like once their bike is gone its gone, so they don\u0027t even file a police report,\u0022 Friedman says. \u0022And then there\u0027s really nothing we can do.\u0022\u000A\u000ASecond, don\u0027t let embarrassment keep you from seeking help. Inform area bike shops to be on the lookout, spam social media to spread the word, and enroll retroactively with national or local bike registries.\u000A\u000AOne thing you shouldn\u0027t do is to seek vengeance. Though it\u0027s tempting to fantasize about vigilante craigslist meet-ups culminating with you riding off into the sunset, it\u0027s not advisable in practice to confront thieves on your own. However, you can still scope craigslist, flea markets and other places that deal secondhand bikes for your missing ride. But if you do get lucky, don\u0027t push that luck. Friedman suggests going only so far as to pose as a buyer before looping in law enforcement to handle the confrontation. \u000A\u000A\u0022Personal safety trumps anything,\u0022 he says. \u0022I\u0027ve run into too many people that can turn on you in an instant.\u0022\u000A\u000ATo recap: Register your bike. Buy a sturdy lock. (Or two.) And if your bike does go missing, don\u0027t give up. Police and digital vigilantes are more than willing to help. Now go outrun that bear.",
  	    "author": ["Jon Terbush"],
  	    "keywords": ["bikes","u-locks","protect your bike","bike thieves"]
